 {\n    58→    \"allow\": [\n    59→      \"*\",\n    60→      \"Bash(go build:*)\",\n    61→      \"Bash(go test:*)\",\n    62→      \"Bash(git commit:*)\",\n    63→      \"Bash(make:*)\"\n    64→    ],\n    65→    \"defaultMode\": \"default\"\n    66→  }\n    67→}\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→The `*` allows most operations, but you can be more restrictive.\n    71→\n    72→Usually I run Claude with:\n    73→\n    74→```bash\n    75→claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --resume --chrome\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→I know, it's dangerous, but I commit continuously and have good backup strategies. This will speed up your work by 10x.\n    79→\n    80→### CLAUDE.md\n    81→\n    82→This file lives in `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` (global) or in your project root (project-specific). It's your way to give Claude persistent instructions.\n    83→\n    84→My global CLAUDE.md:\n    85→\n    86→```markdown\n    87→# Style\n    88→Apply KISS, YAGNI, DRY and SOLID coding principles.\n    89→Always respond in English.\n    90→\n    91→# Rules\n    92→- Do not duplicate logic\n    93→- Do NOT stop until all tasks are complete\n    94→- Check your todo list after each step\n    95→- Never skip failing tests. Fix them!\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→## MCP Servers\n    99→\n   100→MCP (Model Context Protocol) extends Claude's capabilities. I use three:\n   101→\n   102→### mcp.json\n   103→\n   104→```json\n   105→{\n   106→  \"mcpServers\": {\n   107→    \"serena\": {\n   108→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   109→      \"command\": \"uvx\",\n   110→      \"args\": [\"--from\", \"git+https://github.com/oraios/serena\", \"serena-mcp-server\"]\n   111→    },\n   112→    \"chrome-devtools\": {\n   113→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   114→      \"command\": \"npx\",\n   115→      \"args\": [\"chrome-devtools-mcp@latest\"]\n   116→    },\n   117→    \"context7\": {\n   118→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   119→      \"command\": \"npx\",\n   120→      \"args\": [\"-y\", \"@upai/mcp-server-context7\"]\n   121→    }\n   122→  }\n   123→}\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→**What each does:**\n   127→\n   128→- **Serena**: Code intelligence—symbol search, references, project navigation\n   129→- **Chrome DevTools**: Browser automation and debugging\n   130→- **Context7**: Up-to-date documentation lookup for any library\n   131→\n   132→## Plugins\n   133→\n   134→Claude Code has a plugin system. My enabled plugins:\n   135→\n   136→| Plugin | Purpose |\n   137→|--------|---------|\n   138→| context7 | Documentation lookup |\n   139→| feature-dev | Guided feature development |\n   140→| frontend-design | UI/UX design assistance |\n   141→| ralph-wiggum | Automated iteration loops |\n   142→| claude-hud | Status line display |\n   143→\n   144→Enable in settings:\n   145→\n   146→```json\n   147→{\n   148→  \"enabledPlugins\": {\n   149→    \"context7@claude-plugins-official\": true,\n   150→    \"feature-dev@claude-plugins-official\": true,\n   151→    \"claude-hud@claude-hud\": true\n   152→  }\n   153→}\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→## Hooks\n   157→\n   158→Hooks let you run commands before/after Claude actions. I use them for automatic git checkpoints:\n   159→\n   160→```json\n   161→{\n   162→  \"hooks\": {\n   163→    \"PostToolUse\": [\n   164→      {\n   165→        \"matcher\": \"Write|Edit|MultiEdit\",\n   166→        \"hooks\": [\n   167→          {\n   168→            \"type\": \"command\",\n   169→            \"command\": \"git-ai checkpoint claude --hook-input stdin\"\n   170→          }\n   171→        ]\n   172→      }\n   173→    ]\n   174→  }\n   175→}\n   176→```\n   177→\n   178→This creates automatic checkpoints whenever Claude edits files—easy rollback if something goes wrong.\n   179→\n   180→## Status Line\n   181→\n   182→The status line shows useful info while Claude works. I use claude-hud:\n   183→\n   184→```json\n   185→{\n   186→  \"statusLine\": {\n   187→    \"type\": \"command\",\n   188→    \"command\": \"bash -c 'node \\\"$(ls -td ~/.claude/plugins/cache/claude-hud/claude-hud/*/ | head -1)dist/index.js\\\"'\"\n   189→  }\n   190→}\n   191→```\n   192→\n   193→## iTerm 2 Notifications\n   194→\n   195→Never miss when Claude completes a task. In iTerm 2:\n   196→\n   197→1. Open **Preferences → Profiles → Terminal**\n   198→2. Enable **\"Silence bell\"**\n   199→3. Select **\"Send escape sequence-generated alerts\"**\n   200→4. Set your preferred notification delay\n   201→\n   202→This sends a system notification when Claude finishes long-running tasks.\n   203→\n   204→## Makefile Patterns\n   205→\n   206→I use a consistent Makefile structure across all my projects. Here's my typical pattern:\n   207→\n   208→```makefile\n   209→# Variables\n   210→BINARY_NAME=myapp\n   211→MAIN_PATH=./cmd/myapp\n   212→GO=go\n   213→GOFLAGS=-v\n   214→\n   215→# Version info (baked into binary)\n   216→VERSION?=$(shell cat .version 2>/dev/null || echo \"dev\")\n   217→BUILD_TIME=$(shell date -u '+%Y-%m-%d_%H:%M:%S')\n   218→GIT_COMMIT=$(shell git rev-parse --short HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo \"unknown\")\n   219→LDFLAGS=-w -s -X main.Version=$(VERSION) -X main.BuildTime=$(BUILD_TIME) -X main.GitCommit=$(GIT_COMMIT)\n   220→\n   221→# Load .env if exists\n   222→ifneq (,$(wildcard ./.env))\n   223→    include .env\n   224→    export\n   225→endif\n   226→\n   227→.PHONY: all build test clean deploy help\n   228→\n   229→## help: Show this help message\n   230→help:\n   231→\t@echo 'Usage: make <target>'\n   232→\t@sed -n 's/^##//p' ${MAKEFILE_LIST} | column -t -s ':'\n   233→\n   234→## build: Build the binary\n   235→build:\n   236→\t$(GO) build $(GOFLAGS) -ldflags \"$(LDFLAGS)\" -o $(BINARY_NAME) $(MAIN_PATH)\n   237→\n   238→## test: Run all tests\n   239→test:\n   240→\t$(GO) test -v ./...\n   241→\n   242→## test-coverage: Run tests with coverage\n   243→test-coverage:\n   244→\t$(GO) test -coverprofile=coverage.out ./...\n   245→\t$(GO) tool cover -html=coverage.out -o coverage.html\n   246→\n   247→## clean: Remove built artifacts\n   248→clean:\n   249→\trm -f $(BINARY_NAME) coverage.out coverage.html\n   250→\n   251→## deploy: Deploy to remote server\n   252→deploy: build\n   253→\ttar czf /tmp/deploy.tar.gz $(BINARY_NAME)\n   254→\tcat /tmp/deploy.tar.gz | ssh user@host 'cd /app && tar xzf -'\n   255→\trm /tmp/deploy.tar.gz\n   256→```\n   257→\n   258→Key patterns I follow:\n   259→\n   260→- **Self-documenting targets**: Use `## target: description` comments, parsed by `help`\n   261→- **Version injection**: Bake version, build time, and git commit into binaries via LDFLAGS\n   262→- **Environment loading**: Auto-load `.env` files when present\n   263→- **Tar over SSH**: Fast deployment without rsync overhead\n   264→- **Phony targets**: Always declare `.PHONY` for non-file targets\n   265→\n   266→This structure works for Go, but adapts easily to any language.\n   267→\n   268→## Tips from the Creator\n   269→\n   270→[Boris Cherny](https://x.com/bcherny), the creator of Claude Code, shares his approach:\n   271→\n   272→1. **Almost always use Plan mode** - Let Claude think before acting\n   273→2. **Give Claude verification methods** - Unit tests, Chrome extension, or simulators\n   274→3. **Hold the same bar for human and Claude code** - Use `/code-review` to automate review\n   275→4. **Press Shift+Tab** - Toggle auto-accept for file edits, reduces friction\n   276→5. **Remind yourself: \"Claude can probably do this\"** - We underestimate what the model can handle\n   277→\n   278→His setup is surprisingly vanilla—Claude Code works great out of the box. There's no one correct way to use it.\n   279→\n   280→## Tips for Daily Use\n   281→\n   282→1. **Start with `/prime`** - Use a custom command to analyze the project before starting work\n   283→2. **Use opus for complex tasks** - Worth the cost for architecture decisions\n   284→3. **Check the todo list** - Claude tracks its own progress, review it\n   285→4. **Leverage MCP** - Context7 for docs, Serena for code navigation\n   286→5. **Trust but verify** - Always review generated code before committing\n   287→\n   288→## Project-Specific Config\n   289→\n   290→Each project can have its own `.claude/CLAUDE.md` with specific instructions:\n   291→\n   292→```markdown\n   293→# Project: MyApp\n   294→\n   295→## Stack\n   296→- Go 1.22\n   297→- PostgreSQL 15\n   298→- React 18\n   299→\n   300→## Commands\n   301→- `make test` - Run tests\n   302→- `make build` - Build binary\n   303→\n   304→## Conventions\n   305→- Use hexagonal architecture\n   306→- All errors must be wrapped with context\n   307→```\n   308→\n   309→## Conclusion\n   310→\n   311→Claude Code is more than a coding assistant—it's a development environment that understands context, follows instructions, and integrates with your tools. The key is configuration: take time to set up your CLAUDE.md, permissions, and MCP servers.\n   312→\n   313→The investment pays off exponentially.\n   314→\n   315→---\n   316→\n   317→*Questions about my setup? [Reach out on X](https://x.com/StefanoStraus).*\n   318→",
