          "text": "     1→---\n     2→title: My Claude Code Setup\n     3→date: 2025-12-13\n     4→tags: [ai, claude-code, setup, development]\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→# My Claude Code Setup\n     8→\n     9→A complete walkthrough of how I configure Claude Code for maximum productivity.\n    10→\n    11→## What is Claude Code?\n    12→\n    13→Claude Code is Anthropic's official CLI tool that brings Claude directly into your terminal. It's not just a chatbot—it can read files, execute commands, edit code, and integrate with external tools via MCP (Model Context Protocol).\n    14→\n    15→## Installation\n    16→\n    17→```bash\n    18→npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n    19→```\n    20→\n    21→Or if you prefer:\n    22→\n    23→```bash\n    24→brew install claude-code\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→## Configuration Files\n    28→\n    29→Claude Code uses several configuration files in `~/.claude/`:\n    30→\n    31→### settings.json\n    32→\n    33→This is the main configuration file. Here's what matters:\n    34→\n    35→```json\n    36→{\n    37→  \"model\": \"opus\",\n    38→  \"alwaysThinkingEnabled\": true,\n    39→  \"max_turns\": 100,\n    40→  \"includeCoAuthoredBy\": false\n    41→}\n    42→```\n    43→\n    44→Key settings:\n    45→\n    46→- **model**: I use `opus` for complex tasks (expensive but reliable), `sonnet` for everyday work\n    47→- **alwaysThinkingEnabled**: Without thinking even Opus is weak\n    48→- **max_turns**: How many back-and-forth turns before stopping\n    49→- **includeCoAuthoredBy**: Avoid having \"Co-authored-by\" added to git commits\n    50→\n    51→### Permissions\n    52→\n    53→Claude Code has a robust permission system. I prefer a permissive setup with explicit allows:\n    54→\n    55→```json\n    56→{\n    57→  \"permissions\": {\n    58→    \"allow\": [\n    59→      \"*\",\n    60→      \"Bash(go build:*)\",\n    61→      \"Bash(go test:*)\",\n    62→      \"Bash(git commit:*)\",\n    63→      \"Bash(make:*)\"\n    64→    ],\n    65→    \"defaultMode\": \"default\"\n    66→  }\n    67→}\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→The `*` allows most operations, but you can be more restrictive.\n    71→\n    72→Usually I run Claude with:\n    73→\n    74→```bash\n    75→claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --resume --chrome\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→I know, it's dangerous, but I commit continuously and have good backup strategies. This will speed up your work by 10x.\n    79→\n    80→Resume is usefull for a list of previous esession to continue and --chrome will allow browser acces to understand the web content you're building (you need the Claude extension).\n    81→\n    82→### CLAUDE.md\n    83→\n    84→This file lives in `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` (global) or in your project root (project-specific). It's your way to give Claude persistent instructions.\n    85→\n    86→My global CLAUDE.md:\n    87→\n    88→```markdown\n    89→# Style\n    90→Apply KISS, YAGNI, DRY and SOLID coding principles.\n    91→Always respond in English.\n    92→\n    93→# Rules\n    94→- Do not duplicate logic\n    95→- Do NOT stop until all tasks are complete\n    96→- Check your todo list after each step\n    97→- Never skip failing tests. Fix them!\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→## MCP Servers\n   101→\n   102→MCP (Model Context Protocol) extends Claude's capabilities. I use three:\n   103→\n   104→### mcp.json\n   105→\n   106→```json\n   107→{\n   108→  \"mcpServers\": {\n   109→    \"serena\": {\n   110→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   111→      \"command\": \"uvx\",\n   112→      \"args\": [\"--from\", \"git+https://github.com/oraios/serena\", \"serena-mcp-server\"]\n   113→    },\n   114→    \"chrome-devtools\": {\n   115→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   116→      \"command\": \"npx\",\n   117→      \"args\": [\"chrome-devtools-mcp@latest\"]\n   118→    },\n   119→    \"context7\": {\n   120→      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n   121→      \"command\": \"npx\",\n   122→      \"args\": [\"-y\", \"@upai/mcp-server-context7\"]\n   123→    }\n   124→  }\n   125→}\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→**What each does:**\n   129→\n   130→- **Serena**: Code intelligence—symbol search, references, project navigation\n   131→- **Chrome DevTools**: Browser automation and debugging\n   132→- **Context7**: Up-to-date documentation lookup for any library\n   133→\n   134→## Plugins\n   135→\n   136→Claude Code has a plugin system. My enabled plugins:\n   137→\n   138→| Plugin | Purpose |\n   139→|--------|---------|\n   140→| context7 | Documentation lookup |\n   141→| feature-dev | Guided feature development |\n   142→| frontend-design | UI/UX design assistance |\n   143→| ralph-wiggum | Automated iteration loops |\n   144→| claude-hud | Status line display |\n   145→\n   146→Enable in settings:\n   147→\n   148→```json\n   149→{\n   150→  \"enabledPlugins\": {\n   151→    \"context7@claude-plugins-official\": true,\n   152→    \"feature-dev@claude-plugins-official\": true,\n   153→    \"claude-hud@claude-hud\": true\n   154→  }\n   155→}\n   156→```\n   157→\n   158→## Hooks\n   159→\n   160→Hooks let you run commands before/after Claude actions. I use them for automatic git-ai checkpoints:\n   161→\n   162→```json\n   163→{\n   164→  \"hooks\": {\n   165→    \"PostToolUse\": [\n   166→      {\n   167→        \"matcher\": \"Write|Edit|MultiEdit\",\n   168→        \"hooks\": [\n   169→          {\n   170→            \"type\": \"command\",\n   171→            \"command\": \"git-ai checkpoint claude --hook-input stdin\"\n   172→          }\n   173→        ]\n   174→      }\n   175→    ]\n   176→  }\n   177→}\n   178→```\n   179→\n   180→This creates automatic checkpoints to distinguish when AI edited the code and when it was a human activity. Thanks to https://github.com/acunniffe/git-ai\n   181→\n   182→## Status Line\n   183→\n   184→The status line shows useful info while Claude works. I use claude-hud(https://github.com/jarrodwatts/claude-hud):\n   185→\n   186→```json\n   187→{\n   188→  \"statusLine\": {\n   189→    \"type\": \"command\",\n   190→    \"command\": \"bash -c 'node \\\"$(ls -td ~/.claude/plugins/cache/claude-hud/claude-hud/*/ | head -1)dist/index.js\\\"'\"\n   191→  }\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→## iTerm 2 Notifications\n   196→\n   197→Never miss when Claude completes a task. In iTerm 2:\n   198→\n   199→1. Open **Preferences → Profiles → Terminal**\n   200→2. Enable **\"Silence bell\"**\n   201→3. Select **\"Send escape sequence-generated alerts\"**\n   202→4. Set your preferred notification delay\n   203→\n   204→This sends a system notification when Claude finishes long-running tasks.\n   205→\n   206→## Makefile Patterns\n   207→\n   208→I use a consistent Makefile structure across all my projects. Here's my typical pattern:\n   209→\n   210→```makefile\n   211→# Variables\n   212→BINARY_NAME=myapp\n   213→MAIN_PATH=./cmd/myapp\n   214→GO=go\n   215→GOFLAGS=-v\n   216→\n   217→# Version info (baked into binary)\n   218→VERSION?=$(shell cat .version 2>/dev/null || echo \"dev\")\n   219→BUILD_TIME=$(shell date -u '+%Y-%m-%d_%H:%M:%S')\n   220→GIT_COMMIT=$(shell git rev-parse --short HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo \"unknown\")\n   221→LDFLAGS=-w -s -X main.Version=$(VERSION) -X main.BuildTime=$(BUILD_TIME) -X main.GitCommit=$(GIT_COMMIT)\n   222→\n   223→# Load .env if exists\n   224→ifneq (,$(wildcard ./.env))\n   225→    include .env\n   226→    export\n   227→endif\n   228→\n   229→.PHONY: all build test clean deploy help\n   230→\n   231→## help: Show this help message\n   232→help:\n   233→\t@echo 'Usage: make <target>'\n   234→\t@sed -n 's/^##//p' ${MAKEFILE_LIST} | column -t -s ':'\n   235→\n   236→## build: Build the binary\n   237→build:\n   238→\t$(GO) build $(GOFLAGS) -ldflags \"$(LDFLAGS)\" -o $(BINARY_NAME) $(MAIN_PATH)\n   239→\n   240→## test: Run all tests\n   241→test:\n   242→\t$(GO) test -v ./...\n   243→\n   244→## test-coverage: Run tests with coverage\n   245→test-coverage:\n   246→\t$(GO) test -coverprofile=coverage.out ./...\n   247→\t$(GO) tool cover -html=coverage.out -o coverage.html\n   248→\n   249→## clean: Remove built artifacts\n   250→clean:\n   251→\trm -f $(BINARY_NAME) coverage.out coverage.html\n   252→\n   253→## deploy: Deploy to remote server\n   254→deploy: build\n   255→\ttar czf /tmp/deploy.tar.gz $(BINARY_NAME)\n   256→\tcat /tmp/deploy.tar.gz | ssh user@host 'cd /app && tar xzf -'\n   257→\trm /tmp/deploy.tar.gz\n   258→```\n   259→\n   260→Key patterns I follow:\n   261→\n   262→- **Self-documenting targets**: Use `## target: description` comments, parsed by `help`\n   263→- **Version injection**: Bake version, build time, and git commit into binaries via LDFLAGS\n   264→- **Environment loading**: Auto-load `.env` files when present\n   265→- **Tar over SSH**: Fast deployment without rsync overhead\n   266→- **Phony targets**: Always declare `.PHONY` for non-file targets\n   267→\n   268→This structure works for Go, but adapts easily to any language.\n   269→\n   270→## Tips from the Creator\n   271→\n   272→[Boris Cherny](https://x.com/bcherny), the creator of Claude Code, shares his approach:\n   273→\n   274→1. **Almost always use Plan mode** - Let Claude think before acting\n   275→2. **Give Claude verification methods** - Unit tests, Chrome extension, or simulators\n   276→3. **Hold the same bar for human and Claude code** - Use `/code-review` to automate review\n   277→4. **Press Shift+Tab** - Toggle auto-accept for file edits, reduces friction\n   278→5. **Remind yourself: \"Claude can probably do this\"** - We underestimate what the model can handle\n   279→\n   280→His setup is surprisingly vanilla—Claude Code works great out of the box. There's no one correct way to use it.\n   281→\n   282→## Tips for Daily Use\n   283→\n   284→1. **Start with `/prime`** - Use a custom command to analyze the project before starting work\n   285→2. **Use opus for complex tasks** - Worth the cost for architecture decisions\n   286→3. **Check the todo list** - Claude tracks its own progress, review it\n   287→4. **Leverage MCP** - Context7 for docs, Serena for code navigation\n   288→5. **Trust but verify** - Always review generated code before committing\n   289→\n   290→## Project-Specific Config\n   291→\n   292→Each project can have its own `.claude/CLAUDE.md` with specific instructions:\n   293→\n   294→```markdown\n   295→# Project: MyApp\n   296→\n   297→## Stack\n   298→- Go 1.22\n   299→- PostgreSQL 15\n   300→- React 18\n   301→\n   302→## Commands\n   303→- `make test` - Run tests\n   304→- `make build` - Build binary\n   305→\n   306→## Conventions\n   307→- Use hexagonal architecture\n   308→- All errors must be wrapped with context\n   309→```\n   310→\n   311→## Conclusion\n   312→\n   313→Claude Code is more than a coding assistant—it's a development environment that understands context, follows instructions, and integrates with your tools. The key is configuration: take time to set up your CLAUDE.md, permissions, and MCP servers.\n   314→\n   315→The investment pays off exponentially.\n   316→\n   317→---\n   318→\n   319→*Questions about my setup? [Reach out on X](https://x.com/StefanoStraus).*\n   320→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n",
