            "old_string": "## Makefile Patterns\n\nI use a consistent Makefile structure across all my projects. Here's my typical pattern:\n\n```makefile\n# Variables\nBINARY_NAME=myapp\nMAIN_PATH=./cmd/myapp\nGO=go\nGOFLAGS=-v\n\n# Version info (baked into binary)\nVERSION?=$(shell cat .version 2>/dev/null || echo \"dev\")\nBUILD_TIME=$(shell date -u '+%Y-%m-%d_%H:%M:%S')\nGIT_COMMIT=$(shell git rev-parse --short HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo \"unknown\")\nLDFLAGS=-w -s -X main.Version=$(VERSION) -X main.BuildTime=$(BUILD_TIME) -X main.GitCommit=$(GIT_COMMIT)\n\n# Load .env if exists\nifneq (,$(wildcard ./.env))\n    include .env\n    export\nendif\n\n.PHONY: all build test clean deploy help\n\n## help: Show this help message\nhelp:\n\t@echo 'Usage: make <target>'\n\t@sed -n 's/^##//p' ${MAKEFILE_LIST} | column -t -s ':'\n\n## build: Build the binary\nbuild:\n\t$(GO) build $(GOFLAGS) -ldflags \"$(LDFLAGS)\" -o $(BINARY_NAME) $(MAIN_PATH)\n\n## test: Run all tests\ntest:\n\t$(GO) test -v ./...\n\n## test-coverage: Run tests with coverage\ntest-coverage:\n\t$(GO) test -coverprofile=coverage.out ./...\n\t$(GO) tool cover -html=coverage.out -o coverage.html\n\n## clean: Remove built artifacts\nclean:\n\trm -f $(BINARY_NAME) coverage.out coverage.html\n\n## deploy: Deploy to remote server\ndeploy: build\n\ttar czf /tmp/deploy.tar.gz $(BINARY_NAME)\n\tcat /tmp/deploy.tar.gz | ssh user@host 'cd /app && tar xzf -'\n\trm /tmp/deploy.tar.gz\n```\n\nKey patterns I follow:\n\n- **Self-documenting targets**: Use `## target: description` comments, parsed by `help`\n- **Version injection**: Bake version, build time, and git commit into binaries via LDFLAGS\n- **Environment loading**: Auto-load `.env` files when present\n- **Tar over SSH**: Fast deployment without rsync overhead\n- **Phony targets**: Always declare `.PHONY` for non-file targets\n\nThis structure works for Go, but adapts easily to any language."
