mplete before scrolling\n  await new Promise(resolve => {\n    requestAnimationFrame(() => {\n      requestAnimationFrame(() => {\n        this.container.scrollTop = this.container.scrollHeight;\n        resolve();\n      });\n    });\n  });\n\n  await this.typewriter.type(text, line, options);\n  \n  // Scroll again after typing\n  requestAnimationFrame(() => {\n    requestAnimationFrame(() => {\n      this.container.scrollTop = this.container.scrollHeight;\n    });\n  });\n}\n```\n\nI'm exploring a technique to ensure smooth scrolling by using nested `requestAnimationFrame` calls. This approach guarantees that the browser has completed layout calculations before attempting to scroll, which should resolve the issue of cut-off lines. The method involves adding the new line, waiting for layout completion, scrolling, typing the content, and then scrolling again to ensure the entire content is visible.\n\nI'll adjust the padding to 8 pixels and verify if this strategy effectively addresses the rendering and scrolling challenges.",
